+# Solution: Support ORDER BY in SQLite aggregate functions
+
+## Root Cause
+
+SQLite 3.44.0 (released 2023) added support for `ORDER BY` inside aggregate function calls
+(`func(arg [, ...] ORDER BY col [, ...])`). Prior to this fix, EF Core's SQLite provider
+explicitly refused to translate `string.Join` / `string.Concat` aggregate queries that
+included an `.OrderBy` on the input sequence, falling back to (slow and potentially incorrect)
+client-side evaluation. The comment in `SqliteStringAggregateMethodTranslator` read:
+> "SQLite does not support input ordering on aggregate methods."
+
+## Change Description
+
+The fix introduces a new expression node and wires it through the query pipeline:
+
+### New type: `SqliteAggregateFunctionExpression`
+(`src/EFCore.Sqlite.Core/Query/Internal/SqlExpressions/SqliteAggregateFunctionExpression.cs`)
+
+A new `SqlExpression` subclass that holds a function name, arguments, and an ordered list of
+`OrderingExpression` values. When rendered, it emits the SQLite 3.44.0+ syntax:
+
+```sql
+group_concat(arg, sep ORDER BY col DESC)
+```
+
+Modelled after the existing `SqlServerAggregateFunctionExpression` (which uses the different
+`WITHIN GROUP (ORDER BY …)` syntax for SQL Server).
+
+### `SqliteStringAggregateMethodTranslator`
+(`src/EFCore.Sqlite.Core/Query/Internal/Translators/SqliteStringAggregateMethodTranslator.cs`)
+
+Removed the early-return that blocked translation when `source.Orderings.Count > 0`.
+When orderings are present the translator now produces a `SqliteAggregateFunctionExpression`;
+otherwise it falls back to the existing plain `SqlFunctionExpression` path (unchanged).
+
+### `SqliteSqlExpressionFactory`
+(`src/EFCore.Sqlite.Core/Query/Internal/SqliteSqlExpressionFactory.cs`)
+
+Added a `SqliteAggregateFunctionExpression` arm in `ApplyTypeMapping` so that the
+type-mapping postprocessor can propagate type mappings into the new expression node
+(consistent with how `SqlServerSqlExpressionFactory` handles its counterpart).
+
+### `SqliteQuerySqlGenerator`
+(`src/EFCore.Sqlite.Core/Query/Internal/SqliteQuerySqlGenerator.cs`)
+
+Added a `SqliteAggregateFunctionExpression` case to `VisitExtension` and a
+`VisitSqliteAggregateFunction` method that renders:
+
+```
+name(arg1, arg2 ORDER BY col1 ASC, col2 DESC)
+```
+
+### `SqliteSqlNullabilityProcessor`
+(`src/EFCore.Sqlite.Core/Query/Internal/SqliteSqlNullabilityProcessor.cs`)
+
+Added a `SqliteAggregateFunctionExpression` arm to `VisitCustomSqlExpression` and a
+`VisitSqliteAggregateFunction` method that walks arguments and orderings through the
+nullability visitor (consistent with `SqlServerSqlNullabilityProcessor`).
+
+### Test update
+(`test/EFCore.Sqlite.FunctionalTests/Query/Translations/StringTranslationsSqliteTest.cs`)
+
+Updated the `Join_with_ordering` override to expect server-side SQL translation instead of
+the previous client-side fallback SQL.
+
+## Files Edited
+
+| File | Change |
+|------|--------|
+| `src/EFCore.Sqlite.Core/Query/Internal/SqlExpressions/SqliteAggregateFunctionExpression.cs` | **New** — expression node for aggregate + ORDER BY |
+| `src/EFCore.Sqlite.Core/Query/Internal/Translators/SqliteStringAggregateMethodTranslator.cs` | Removed ordering guard; branch on orderings to pick new expression type |
+| `src/EFCore.Sqlite.Core/Query/Internal/SqliteSqlExpressionFactory.cs` | `ApplyTypeMapping` case for new expression |
+| `src/EFCore.Sqlite.Core/Query/Internal/SqliteQuerySqlGenerator.cs` | SQL generation for new expression |
+| `src/EFCore.Sqlite.Core/Query/Internal/SqliteSqlNullabilityProcessor.cs` | Nullability processing for new expression |
+| `test/EFCore.Sqlite.FunctionalTests/Query/Translations/StringTranslationsSqliteTest.cs` | Updated expected SQL for `Join_with_ordering` |
+
+## Precedent Usage
+
+### Query 1: "SQLite aggregate function ORDER BY support"
+Result: BELOW THRESHOLD (score 0.320) — PR #37619 (non-finite double Julian date parsing).
+Not useful.
+
+### Query 2: "aggregate function ORDER BY ordering within aggregate"
+Result: BELOW THRESHOLD (score 0.331) — PR #37573 (MinBy/MaxBy support).
+Not directly useful for the implementation approach, but confirmed the aggregate translation
+pattern. Ignored for implementation decisions; the `SqlServerAggregateFunctionExpression`
+pattern in the existing codebase was the authoritative reference instead.
